example.p:
This system of equations can be rewritten as the matrix equation\begin{bmatrix}
            1&1&0&0\\1&0&-2&0\\0&0&0&1\\0&1&0&-1
            \end{bmatrix}
            \colvector{(a_1-a_2)\\(b_1-b_2)\\(c_1-c_2)\\(d_1-d_2)}=\colvector{0\\0\\0\\0}.

statement.p:
Suppose \ltdefn{T}{U}{V} is a linear transformation and \vect{v}\in V.  If the preimage \preimage{T}{\vect{v}} is nonempty, and \vect{u}\in\preimage{T}{\vect{v}}  then\preimage{T}{\vect{v}}=
                \setparts{\vect{u}+\vect{z}}{\vect{z}\in\krn{T}}
                =\vect{u}+\krn{T}.

proof.p:
Let M=\setparts{\vect{u}+\vect{z}}{\vect{z}\in\krn{T}}.  First, we show that M\subseteq\preimage{T}{\vect{v}}.  Suppose that \vect{w}\in M, so \vect{w} has the form \vect{w}=\vect{u}+\vect{z}, where \vect{z}\in\krn{T}.  Then
                    \lteval{T}{\vect{w}}&=\lteval{T}{\vect{u}+\vect{z}}
                    &=\lteval{T}{\vect{u}}+\lteval{T}{\vect{z}}&&

                    &=\vect{v}+\zerovector&&\vect{u}\in\preimage{T}{\vect{v}},\ \vect{z}\in\krn{T}
                    &=\vect{v}&&

                which qualifies \vect{w} for membership in the preimage of \vect{v}, \vect{w}\in\preimage{T}{\vect{v}}.

