case.p:
To establish that T is injective, appeal to  and begin with the assumption that \lteval{T}{\vect{x}}=\lteval{T}{\vect{y}}.  Then
                      \lteval{T}{\vect{x}-\vect{y}}
                      &=\lteval{T}{\vect{x}}-\lteval{T}{\vect{y}}&&

                      &=\zerovector&&
                          \text{Hypothesis}
                  .

So \vect{x}-\vect{y}\in\krn{T} by  and with the hypothesis that the kernel is trivial we conclude that \vect{x}-\vect{y}=\zerovector.  Then
                        \vect{y}
                        =\vect{y}+\zerovector
                        =\vect{y}+\left(\vect{x}-\vect{y}\right)
                        =\vect{x}
                    thus establishing that T is injective by .

example.p:
The key is the vector\vect{z}=\colvector{3\\4\\1\\3\\3}which you can check is an element of \krn{T} for Archetype.  Choose a vector \vect{x} at random, and then compute \vect{y}=\vect{x}+\vect{z} (verify this computation back in ).  Then
                \lteval{T}{\vect{y}}&=\lteval{T}{\vect{x}+\vect{z}}
                &=\lteval{T}{\vect{x}}+\lteval{T}{\vect{z}}&&

                &=\lteval{T}{\vect{x}}+\zerovector&&\vect{z}\in\krn{T}
                &=\lteval{T}{\vect{x}}&&

            .

statement.p:
Suppose that \ltdefn{T}{U}{V} is an injective linear transformation and
                S&=\set{\vectorlist{u}{t}}
            is a linearly independent subset of U.  Then
                R&=\set{\lteval{T}{\vect{u}_1},\,\lteval{T}{\vect{u}_2},\,\lteval{T}{\vect{u}_3},\,\ldots,\,\lteval{T}{\vect{u}_t}}
            is a linearly independent subset of V.

Suppose that \ltdefn{T}{U}{V} is a linear transformation and
                    B&=\set{\vectorlist{u}{m}}
                is a basis of U.  Then T is injective if and only if
                    C&=\set{\lteval{T}{\vect{u}_1},\,\lteval{T}{\vect{u}_2},\,\lteval{T}{\vect{u}_3},\,\ldots,\,\lteval{T}{\vect{u}_m}}
                is a linearly independent subset of V.

The linear transformation \ltdefn{T}{\complex{4}}{\complex{3}} is not injective.  Find two inputs \vect{x},\,\vect{y}\in\complex{4} that yield the same output (that is \lteval{T}{\vect{x}}=\lteval{T}{\vect{y}}).\lteval{T}{\colvector{x_1\\x_2\\x_3\\x_4}}=
                \colvector{
                2x_1+x_2+x_3\\
                -x_1+3x_2+x_3-x_4\\
                3x_1+x_2+2x_3-2x_4
                }.

solution.p:
A linear transformation that is not injective will have a nontrivial kernel (), and this is the key to finding the desired inputs.  We need one nontrivial element of the kernel, so suppose that \vect{z}\in\complex{4} is an element of the kernel,\colvector{0\\0\\0}
                =\zerovector
                =\lteval{T}{\vect{z}}
                =\colvector{
                2z_1+z_2+z_3\\
                -z_1+3z_2+z_3-z_4\\
                3z_1+z_2+2z_3-2z_4
                }.  Vector equality  leads to the homogeneous system of three equations in four variables,
                    2z_1+z_2+z_3&=0
                    -z_1+3z_2+z_3-z_4&=0
                    3z_1+z_2+2z_3-2z_4&=0
                .  The coefficient matrix of this system row-reduces as\begin{bmatrix}
                 2 & 1 & 1 & 0 \\
                 -1 & 3 & 1 & -1 \\
                 3 & 1 & 2 & -2
                \end{bmatrix}
                \rref
                \begin{bmatrix}
                 \leading{1} & 0 & 0 & 1 \\
                 0 & \leading{1} & 0 & 1 \\
                 0 & 0 & \leading{1} & -3
                \end{bmatrix}.  From this we can find a solution (we only need one), that is an element of \krn{T},\vect{z}=\colvector{-1\\-1\\3\\1}.  Now, we choose a vector \vect{x} at random and set \vect{y}=\vect{x}+\vect{z},
                    \vect{x}
                    &=\colvector{2\\3\\4\\-2}
                    &
                    \vect{y}&=\vect{x}+\vect{z}=
                    \colvector{2\\3\\4\\-2}+\colvector{-1\\-1\\3\\1}
                    =\colvector{1\\2\\7\\-1}
                and you can check that\lteval{T}{\vect{x}}
                =\colvector{11\\13\\21}
                =\lteval{T}{\vect{y}}.  A quicker solution is to take two elements of the kernel (in this case, scalar multiples of \vect{z}) which both get sent to \zerovector by T.  Quicker yet, take \zerovector and \vect{z} as \vect{x} and \vect{y}, which also both get sent to \zerovector by T.

To find the kernel, we require all \vect{x}\in\complex{3} such that \lteval{T}{\vect{x}}=\zerovector.  This condition is\colvector{2x_1-x_2+5x_3\\-4x_1+2x_2-10x_3}=\colvector{0\\0}.  This leads to a homogeneous system of two linear equations in three variables, whose coefficient matrix row-reduces to\begin{bmatrix}
                \leading{1} & -\frac{1}{2} & \frac{5}{2}\\
                0 & 0 & 0
                \end{bmatrix}.  With two free variables  yields the basis for the null space\set{
                \colvector{-\frac{5}{2}\\0\\1},\,
                \colvector{\frac{1}{2}\\1\\0}
                }.

With 
ullity{T}
eq 0, \krn{T}
eq\set{\zerovector}, so says T is not injective.

Since T is given by matrix multiplication, \krn{T} = \nsp{A}.  We have
                    \begin{bmatrix}
                    1 & 2 & 3 & 1\\
                    2 & -1 & 1 & 0\\
                    1 & 2 & -1 & -2 \\
                    1 & 3 & 2 & 1
                    \end{bmatrix}
                    &\rref
                    \begin{bmatrix}
                    \leading{1} & 0 & 0 & 0\\
                    0 & \leading{1} & 0 & 0\\
                    0 & 0 & \leading{1} & 0\\
                    0 & 0 & 0 & \leading{1}
                    \end{bmatrix}
                .  The null space of A is \set{\zerovector}, so the kernel of T is also trivial:  \krn{T} = \set{\zerovector}.

statement.p:
Given that the linear transformation \ltdefn{T}{\complex{3}}{\complex{3}}, \lteval{T}{\colvector{x\\y\\z}} = \colvector{2x + y\\2y + z\\x + 2z} is injective, show directly that \set{
                \lteval{T}{\vect{e}_1},\,
                \lteval{T}{\vect{e}_2},\,
                \lteval{T}{\vect{e}_3}
                } is a linearly independent set.

solution.p:
We have
                    \lteval{T}{\vect{e}_1} &= \colvector{2\\0\\1}
                    &
                    \lteval{T}{\vect{e}_2} &= \colvector{1\\2\\0}
                    &
                    \lteval{T}{\vect{e}_3} &= \colvector{0\\1\\2}
                .  Let us put these vectors into a matrix and row reduce to test their linear independence.
                    \begin{bmatrix}
                    2 & 1 & 0\\
                    0 & 2 & 1\\
                    1 & 0 & 2
                    \end{bmatrix}
                    &\rref
                    \begin{bmatrix}
                    \leading{1} & 0 & 0\\
                    0 & \leading{1} & 0\\
                    0 & 0 & \leading{1}
                    \end{bmatrix}
                so the set of vectors \set{\lteval{T}{\vect{e}_1},\, \lteval{T}{\vect{e}_1},\,\lteval{T}{\vect{e}_1}} is linearly independent.

statement.p:
Given that the linear transformation \ltdefn{T}{\complex{2}}{\complex{3}}, \lteval{T}{\colvector{x\\y}} = \colvector{x+y\\2x + y\\x + 2y} is injective, show directly that \set{
                \lteval{T}{\vect{e}_1},\,
                \lteval{T}{\vect{e}_2}
                } is a linearly independent set.

solution.p:
We have \lteval{T}{\vect{e}_1} = \colvector{1\\2\\1} and \lteval{T}{\vect{e}_2} = \colvector{1\\1\\2}.  Putting these into a matrix as columns and row-reducing, we have
                    \begin{bmatrix}
                    1 & 1\\
                    2 & 1\\
                    1 & 2
                    \end{bmatrix}
                    &\rref
                    \begin{bmatrix}
                    \leading{1} & 0 \\
                    0 & \leading{1}\\
                    0 & 0
                    \end{bmatrix}
                .  Thus, the set of vectors \set{\lteval{T}{\vect{e}_1},\,\lteval{T}{\vect{e}_2}} is linearly independent.

statement.p:
Given that the linear transformation \ltdefn{T}{\complex{3}}{\complex{5}}, \lteval{T}{\colvector{x\\y\\z}} =
                \begin{bmatrix}
                1 & 3 & 2\\
                0 & 1 & 1\\
                1 & 2 & 1\\
                1 & 0 & 1\\
                3 & 1 & 2
                \end{bmatrix}
                \colvector{x\\y\\z} is injective, show directly that \set{
                \lteval{T}{\vect{e}_1},\,
                \lteval{T}{\vect{e}_2},\,
                \lteval{T}{\vect{e}_3}
                } is a linearly independent set.

solution.p:
We have
                    \lteval{T}{\vect{e}_1} &= \colvector{1\\0\\1\\1\\3}
                    &
                    \lteval{T}{\vect{e}_2} &= \colvector{3\\1\\2\\0\\1}
                    &
                    \lteval{T}{\vect{e}_3} &= \colvector{2\\1\\1\\1\\2}
                .  Apply  to test the linear independence of T.
                    \begin{bmatrix}
                    1 & 3 & 2\\
                    0 & 1 & 1\\
                    1 & 2 & 1\\
                    1 & 0 & 1\\
                    3 & 1 & 2
                    \end{bmatrix}
                    &\rref
                    \begin{bmatrix}
                    \leading{1} & 0 & 0\\
                    0 & \leading{1} & 0\\
                    0 & 0 & \leading{1} \\
                    0 & 0 & 0\\
                    0 & 0 & 0
                    \end{bmatrix}
                so since r = 3 = n, the set of vectors \set{\lteval{T}{\vect{e}_1},\,\lteval{T}{\vect{e}_2},\,\lteval{T}{\vect{e}_3}} is linearly independent.

We choose \vect{x} to be any vector we like.  A particularly cocky choice would be to choose \vect{x}=\zerovector, but we will instead choose\vect{x}= \begin{bmatrix} 2 & -1 \\ -1 & 4 \end{bmatrix}.  Then \lteval{R}{\vect{x}}=9+9x.  Now compute the kernel of R, which by  we expect to be nontrivial.  Setting \lteval{R}{\begin{bmatrix}a&b\\b&c\end{bmatrix}} equal to the zero vector, \zerovector=0+0x, and equating coefficients leads to a homogeneous system of equations.  Row-reducing the coefficient matrix of this system will allow us to determine the values of a, b and c that create elements of the null space of R,\begin{bmatrix}
                 2 & -1 & 1 \\
                 1 & 1 & 2
                \end{bmatrix}
                \rref
                \begin{bmatrix}
                 \leading{1} & 0 & 1 \\
                 0 & \leading{1} & 1
                \end{bmatrix}.  We only need a single element of the null space of this coefficient matrix, so we will not compute a precise description of the whole null space.  Instead, choose the free variable c=2.  Then\vect{z}=\begin{bmatrix} -2 & -2 \\ -2 & 2\end{bmatrix}is the corresponding element of the kernel.  We compute the desired \vect{y} as\vect{y}=\vect{x}+\vect{z}=
                \begin{bmatrix} 2 & -1 \\ -1 & 4 \end{bmatrix}
                +
                \begin{bmatrix} -2 & -2 \\ -2 & 2\end{bmatrix}
                =
                \begin{bmatrix}  0 & -3 \\ -3 & 6 \end{bmatrix}.  Then check that \lteval{R}{\vect{y}}=9+9x.
